                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc>
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support><term>monument</term> Gwynedd Archaeological Trust Regional Historic Environment Record: <ref target="https://archwilio.org.uk/her/"><idno type="HER">3033</idno>Penseri Farm (Penseri Bach, Penseiri Bach)</ref>
                                    <material>Stone</material> <objectType>pillar</objectType>, described as <q>brown weathering, grey-green coarse-grained sandstone...derived from the local Ordovician strata...[which] occur 1.5km to the north-west</q><bibl><ptr target="EDW2013"/>Edwards 2013<citedRange unit="page">163</citedRange></bibl>. 
                                    <dimensions unit="m">
                                        <height>1.6</height>
                                        <width>0.45</width>
                                       <depth>0.35</depth></dimensions></support>
                                <condition/>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout>The stone is inscribed with a Roman-letter inscription in the centre of its largest smooth face just beneath a diagonal fault line. The inscription is in one line reading vertically downwards. The stone is also inscribed with an Ogham inscription in one line on the right-hand edge of the face inscribed with Roman letters. The Ogham inscription reads vertically upwards. Both inscriptions are <rs type="execution" key="incised" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/1.html">incised</rs><bibl><ptr target="EDW2013"/>Edwards 2013<citedRange unit="page">163</citedRange></bibl>.</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>The characters in the Roman-letter inscription are capitals <q>MA are ligatures, the strokes are widely spaced and touch the line; the horizontal of the L slopes downwards below the line and the second smaller I is tucked above; S is larger; final I is horizontal [...] The roman-letter capitals, though not evenly set out, do appear ordered and are visually pleasing<bibl><ptr target="EDW2013"/>Edwards 2013<citedRange unit="page">163-5</citedRange></bibl>.</q> About the Ogham inscription, the Welsh Corpus notes that <q>the position of the ogams, on the right angle of [the Roman-letter inscribed face] rather than on the left, is less usual, but their closeness to the roman-letter inscription was presumably to indicate that one was the translation of the other <bibl><ptr target="EDW2013"/>Edwards 2013<citedRange unit="page">165</citedRange></bibl>.</q>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
